explanation:
For determining whether any operations inside OS_rename are dead code you must know which calls/operations can actually execute and whether they have observable side effects. Each symbol is required for the following reason:

- OS_TranslatePath: Determines whether the function proceeds (sets return_code). If it always fails/succeeds in a given configuration the downstream code may be dead/active.
- OS_FileRename_Impl: Performs the file-system rename; required to see if this operation has observable effects (and whether its presence/absence affects behaviour).
- OS_ObjectIdIterateActive: Initializes/starts the object-id iterator; needed to know if the subsequent iterator-based loop is entered and what side effects this initialization may have.
- OS_ObjectIdIteratorGetNext: Controls whether the while-loop body runs; required to determine if the loop body is ever executed (if never true, body is dead code).
- OS_ObjectIdIteratorDestroy: Called at the end of iteration; may have side effects (transaction cancelation/cleanup) so its execution cannot be assumed dead without its definition.
- OS_ObjectIdTransactionCancel: (callee of Destroy) May perform observable effects when iterator destroyed; needed to assess whether the destroy call is semantically relevant.
- OS_OBJECT_TABLE_GET: Macro/inline used to obtain stream pointer from the token; needed to know whether accessing/modifying stream entries has side effects (indexing, bounds checks, assertions) and how token maps to table index.
- OS_ObjectIndexFromToken: Likely used by OBJECT_TABLE_GET or related indexing; required to understand how iter.token maps into the object table and whether that mapping can fail or have side effects.
- OS_stream_table: The global table being indexed/modified; required to see if accessing or modifying its entries has observable global effect.
- OS_stream_internal_record_t: Type of stream entries; required to know the layout (stream_name buffer size, socket_domain field) to assess whether the strncpy and the condition are meaningful/valid.
- OS_object_iter_t: Iterator type (contains token etc.); needed to know iterator semantics, token field location and lifetime to determine if the iteration is meaningful.
- OS_MAX_LOCAL_PATH_LEN: Buffer size used for path translation; needed to know if path translations/truncations occur and whether those assignments are relevant.
- OS_SUCCESS: Return-code constant used for flow control; required to reason about which branches are executed and thus if code is reachable/executable.
- OS_SocketDomain_INVALID: Used in the loop condition to filter which streams are updated; needed to know whether the condition can be true and thus whether the assignment to stream_name can occur.
- strcmp: Determines whether stream->stream_name matches the old name; required to know if the conditional that leads to the strncpy can ever be true.
- strncpy: Performs the modification of the stream name; required to determine whether that write is an observable effect (i.e. not dead) and whether it might overflow/truncate.

Collectively these symbols define the control flow (return_code checks and iterator loop), the data targets (stream table and fields), and the potential side effects (file-system rename, iterator destroy/transaction cancel, modification of global stream entries). Without them you cannot decide whether the operations in OS_rename are removable without changing program behaviour (i.e. dead code).
